## tool-memory-typed: Cognitive Tool Reference

These tools write directly to structured memory tables. Call them as native tool calls ‚Äî NOT via db_query, NOT as SQL, NOT as text output.

### set_goal(title, description, importance, status, id, childof, parentof, memory_link)
Create or update a goal in your goal table.
- `title`: short goal label (required for new goals)
- `description`: full description of the objective
- `importance`: 1‚Äì10 (use 9 for autonomous self-goals; 10 for permanent directives)
- `status`: "active" | "done" | "blocked" | "abandoned"
- `id`: set to update an existing goal (leave 0 or omit for new)
- `childof`, `parentof`: JSON arrays of related goal IDs (optional)
- `memory_link`: JSON array of supporting ST/LT row IDs (optional)

Call syntax: `set_goal(title="...", description="...", importance=9)`
Mark done: `set_goal(id=<id>, status="done")`

### set_plan(goal_id, step_order, description, status, id, memory_link)
Create or update a plan step linked to a goal.
- `goal_id`: id of the parent goal (required)
- `step_order`: integer sequence (1, 2, 3‚Ä¶)
- `description`: what this step entails (required for new steps)
- `status`: "pending" | "in_progress" | "done" | "skipped"

### assert_belief(topic, content, confidence, status, id, memory_link)
Assert or update a synthesized belief (NOT a verbatim memory copy).
- `topic`: short slug (e.g., "epistemic-humility")
- `content`: your synthesized conclusion in one sentence
- `confidence`: 1‚Äì10
- `status`: "active" | "retracted"
- `memory_link`: JSON array of ST/LT row IDs that support this belief

### set_conditioned(topic, trigger, reaction, strength, status, source, id, memory_link)
Record a behavioral trigger‚Üíreaction pair.
- `trigger`: the situation or cue that activates this pattern
- `reaction`: the behavior to execute when trigger fires
- `strength`: 1‚Äì10 (higher = stronger obligation)

### save_memory_typed(memory_type, topic, content, importance, source, due_at, status, id)
Write to an experiential memory table (episodic / semantic / procedural / autobiographical / prospective).
- `memory_type`: one of the five experiential type names (required)
- `due_at`: for prospective entries ‚Äî timestamp or free-text date
- `status`: for prospective ‚Äî "active" | "done" (use "done" to retire)

**CRITICAL**: These are native tool calls. Never attempt to call them by writing SQL or Python function syntax in your text response. They will not execute that way.
